So you need to do an
integration by parts

00:02:57.780 --> 00:03:02.130
plus a total derivative term,
or plus a total derivative term

00:03:02.130 --> 00:03:07.160
until the derivative term we
induce a term on the boundary

00:03:07.160 --> 00:03:08.285
if you have an open string.

00:03:21.931 --> 00:03:26.170
Say at sigma equal to 0 and pi.

00:03:26.170 --> 00:03:28.670
OK?

00:03:28.670 --> 00:03:35.280
So this is still d tau.

00:03:35.280 --> 00:03:44.230
And so from this term, you
get equation of motion.

00:03:46.770 --> 00:03:50.406
And then you induce a
boundary term, evaluate it.

00:03:50.406 --> 00:03:55.110
If it's open string, there's
two boundaries, at 0 and pi.

00:03:55.110 --> 00:03:57.350
To do such a boundary
term at the boundary,

00:03:57.350 --> 00:04:01.840
we need to also get
rid of-- otherwise,

00:04:01.840 --> 00:04:05.240
the equation of motion
is not satisfied.

00:04:05.240 --> 00:04:07.450
And what we discussed
is [INAUDIBLE]

00:04:07.450 --> 00:04:09.850
Neumann boundary conditions.

00:04:09.850 --> 00:04:13.410
It's just taking the pi of
sigma equal to 0, pi of sigma x

00:04:13.410 --> 00:04:15.190
mu to be 0.

00:04:15.190 --> 00:04:21.046
But in general, for
any mu, say for any mu,

00:04:21.046 --> 00:04:24.150
you have a choice of
four boundary conditions.

00:04:24.150 --> 00:04:28.120
You can choose delta
x mu equal to 0,

00:04:28.120 --> 00:04:33.550
or partial sigma
x mu equal to 0.

00:04:33.550 --> 00:04:38.790
Say and sigma equal to 0.

00:04:38.790 --> 00:04:42.030
And you have the same
choices at sigma equal to pi.

00:04:44.600 --> 00:04:49.020
So altogether, you have
actually four possible boundary

00:04:49.020 --> 00:04:51.535
conditions for each direction.

00:04:51.535 --> 00:04:54.430
So for each direction, you
have four possible boundary

00:04:54.430 --> 00:04:55.070
conditions.

00:04:55.070 --> 00:04:56.861
If you can see the all
possible directions,

00:04:56.861 --> 00:04:59.510
there are many, many
different boundary conditions.

00:04:59.510 --> 00:05:00.431
OK?

00:05:00.431 --> 00:05:02.680
There are, in principle,
many, many different boundary

00:05:02.680 --> 00:05:05.190
conditions.

00:05:05.190 --> 00:05:08.420
So let's now look at what the
other boundary conditions mean.

00:05:08.420 --> 00:05:09.810
OK?

00:05:09.810 --> 00:05:12.600
We looked at the case which
the-- you just imposed this

00:05:12.600 --> 00:05:17.080
everywhere, at both sigma equal
to 0 and sigma equal to pi,

00:05:17.080 --> 00:05:18.490
and the four directions.

00:05:18.490 --> 00:05:21.750
But now let us explore
these more general boundary

00:05:21.750 --> 00:05:24.430
conditions.

00:05:24.430 --> 00:05:30.441
First let's just quickly look at
what this boundary-- so this is

00:05:30.441 --> 00:05:31.940
called Dirichlet
boundary condition,

00:05:31.940 --> 00:05:33.537
this is called the Neumann.

00:05:33.537 --> 00:05:36.120
So first let's look at what does
this boundary condition mean.

00:05:36.120 --> 00:05:36.619
OK?

00:05:39.950 --> 00:05:42.420
So if we have-- say let's
consider some direction,

00:05:42.420 --> 00:05:45.740
i, set delta xi equal to 0.

00:05:49.270 --> 00:05:55.200
Say at sigma equal to
0, say tau equal to 0.

00:05:55.200 --> 00:05:58.310
So this is the example of
this Dirichlet boundary

00:05:58.310 --> 00:06:00.600
condition in the i direction.

00:06:00.600 --> 00:06:07.040
Say suppose that sigma equal to
0, you have-- you impose this.

00:06:07.040 --> 00:06:13.170
So what this means is that
the vibration of xi at sigma

00:06:13.170 --> 00:06:16.030
equal to 0 at all
time does not change.

00:06:16.030 --> 00:06:20.080
So tau is like a parameter
I should watch it-- time,

00:06:20.080 --> 00:06:22.290
the watch it motion.

00:06:22.290 --> 00:06:26.900
So this tells you that, at
all time, the value of the xi

00:06:26.900 --> 00:06:29.730
does not change at the endpoint.

00:06:29.730 --> 00:06:33.500
So what this means,
this directly

00:06:33.500 --> 00:06:38.730
translates into xi
sigma equal to 0,

00:06:38.730 --> 00:06:42.040
and tau should be a constant.

00:06:42.040 --> 00:06:43.036
OK?

00:06:43.036 --> 00:06:45.690
Should be a constant.

00:06:45.690 --> 00:06:47.630
So this is the
Dirichlet condition.

00:06:52.460 --> 00:06:54.140
And so let's look
at some examples

00:06:54.140 --> 00:06:58.960
to understand a little
bit more explicitly

00:06:58.960 --> 00:07:01.900
what this kind of
condition-- want

00:07:01.900 --> 00:07:04.080
this Dirichlet condition means.

00:07:04.080 --> 00:07:05.360
OK?

00:07:05.360 --> 00:07:08.010
So let's first
consider the example.

00:07:08.010 --> 00:07:18.250
Say suppose in all directions,
say from 0 to d minus 2,

00:07:18.250 --> 00:07:29.630
OK, we use-- suppose use
Neumann boundary condition

00:07:29.630 --> 00:07:37.680
as what we did before for
both sigma equal to 0 and pi.

00:07:37.680 --> 00:07:40.865
But for the last
coordinate, [INAUDIBLE]

00:07:40.865 --> 00:07:48.890
xt minus 1, so let's impose the
Dirichlet boundary condition.

00:07:48.890 --> 00:07:54.970
So let's take it to be
A at sigma-- both sigma

00:07:54.970 --> 00:07:55.750
and 0 equal to pi.

00:07:55.750 --> 00:07:56.250
OK?

00:07:56.250 --> 00:07:58.470
So for the moment, let's
take the boundary condition

00:07:58.470 --> 00:08:03.830
to be same at both
sigma equal to 0 and pi.

00:08:03.830 --> 00:08:07.020
So let's look at what
did this condition means.

00:08:07.020 --> 00:08:08.465
Let's look at this example.

00:08:12.980 --> 00:08:16.710
So what this condition means--
so let's draw a figure.

00:08:22.490 --> 00:08:24.250
So, I cannot draw
many directions.

00:08:24.250 --> 00:08:28.250
In particular, I cannot
draw 6x26 dimensions.

00:08:28.250 --> 00:08:31.895
So let me call the
horizontal axis as all the--

00:08:31.895 --> 00:08:37.240
the connection of all the
dimensions up to d minus 2.

00:08:37.240 --> 00:08:41.419
And under this axis
is the d minus 1.

00:08:41.419 --> 00:08:41.918
OK?

00:08:46.130 --> 00:08:52.750
Then the endpoint, the x d minus
1 equal to a at the endpoint--

00:08:52.750 --> 00:08:56.870
so suppose that this is
the line of x equal to a.

00:09:02.890 --> 00:09:07.955
So suppose this is the
hypersurface for x equals-- x d

00:09:07.955 --> 00:09:12.820
minus 1 equal to a, then that
boundary condition tells you

00:09:12.820 --> 00:09:16.890
that whatever open
string the motion,

00:09:16.890 --> 00:09:21.580
the endpoint must be restricted
to this hypersurface.

00:09:21.580 --> 00:09:22.182
OK?

00:09:22.182 --> 00:09:23.890
So that's what this--
geometrically, what

00:09:23.890 --> 00:09:26.130
this condition means.

00:09:26.130 --> 00:09:28.810
It just says, let's
consider xt minus 1

00:09:28.810 --> 00:09:32.140
equal to a, which is a
hypersurface in spacetime,

00:09:32.140 --> 00:09:39.760
and then this condition means
that the endpoint of the string

00:09:39.760 --> 00:09:42.660
must be restricted
to this surface.

00:09:42.660 --> 00:09:44.180
The interior of
the string can be

00:09:44.180 --> 00:09:47.680
any-- can be out-- can
have no restriction,

00:09:47.680 --> 00:09:50.491
but the endpoint have
to be on this surface.

00:09:50.491 --> 00:09:50.990
OK?

00:09:50.990 --> 00:09:51.573
Is this clear?

00:09:55.020 --> 00:09:55.670
OK.

00:09:55.670 --> 00:09:57.990
So you can generalize.

00:09:57.990 --> 00:09:59.410
So this is the first example.

00:09:59.410 --> 00:10:00.300
You can generalize.

00:10:00.300 --> 00:10:06.262
Let's consider x from
0 to some value, p.

00:10:06.262 --> 00:10:08.190
Of course, p is smaller
than the total number

00:10:08.190 --> 00:10:15.120
of dimensions, which is n
for sigma at 0 and the pi.

00:10:15.120 --> 00:10:28.170
And then the rest-- say xp plus
1, xp plus 2, to xp minus 1,

00:10:28.170 --> 00:10:34.600
these directions we impose the
Dirichlet boundary conditions.

00:10:34.600 --> 00:10:39.580
And then let me call
this one back to a.

00:10:39.580 --> 00:10:40.790
So I'm back to a.

00:10:40.790 --> 00:10:44.410
For both sigma
equal to 0 and pi.

00:10:44.410 --> 00:10:44.940
OK?

00:10:44.940 --> 00:10:47.460
So a is just some constant
vector of the same dimension

00:10:47.460 --> 00:10:50.770
as the number of x here.

00:10:50.770 --> 00:10:53.270
The same as the
number of x here.

00:10:53.270 --> 00:10:55.660
And this is just
a more general way

00:10:55.660 --> 00:10:57.980
to impose this to
more directions.

00:10:57.980 --> 00:10:58.480
OK?

00:11:03.150 --> 00:11:06.280
Is this notation clear?

00:11:06.280 --> 00:11:06.780
Yes?

