AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:13:18.680 --> 00:13:19.390
HONG LIU: Yeah.

00:13:19.390 --> 00:13:21.540
We are talking
about how to impose

00:13:21.540 --> 00:13:24.450
the-- what's the meaning of
imposing the Dirichlet boundary

00:13:24.450 --> 00:13:26.650
condition.

00:13:26.650 --> 00:13:29.340
Instead of Neumann
boundary condition.

00:13:29.340 --> 00:13:31.530
So we now impose the
Dirichlet boundary condition,

00:13:31.530 --> 00:13:34.300
which goes one into the
[INAUDIBLE] of the endpoint

00:13:34.300 --> 00:13:36.440
should be 0.

00:13:36.440 --> 00:13:39.280
And then this can be
specified by the endpoint

00:13:39.280 --> 00:13:41.490
if you take some constant value.

00:13:41.490 --> 00:13:45.120
And so that's the
geometric way to think

00:13:45.120 --> 00:13:48.015
about these different
Dirichlet boundary conditions.

00:13:53.720 --> 00:13:59.230
So if you look at this
naively, so previously, when

00:13:59.230 --> 00:14:04.630
we can see the Neumann boundary
condition for all directions,

00:14:04.630 --> 00:14:09.720
then the string-- then there's
no restriction to the string.

00:14:09.720 --> 00:14:12.360
Then the string
can move anywhere.

00:14:12.360 --> 00:14:14.760
So now when you-- when
in some directions

00:14:14.760 --> 00:14:17.220
we impose the
Dirichlet condition,

00:14:17.220 --> 00:14:20.590
then we see that-- then
the motion of the string

00:14:20.590 --> 00:14:23.330
get restricted, and
that this endpoint now

00:14:23.330 --> 00:14:27.410
have to [INAUDIBLE] some soft
dimension of the spacetime.

00:14:27.410 --> 00:14:29.500
OK?

00:14:29.500 --> 00:14:32.390
So at first sight, this may
seem to be a nonsensical thing

00:14:32.390 --> 00:14:34.080
to do.

00:14:34.080 --> 00:14:37.640
Just say-- you ask
why somehow I have

00:14:37.640 --> 00:14:42.050
to restrict some open
strings to some sub-manifold

00:14:42.050 --> 00:14:44.430
in the spacetime.

00:14:44.430 --> 00:14:46.310
So why should I do that?

00:14:46.310 --> 00:14:49.167
In particular, that breaks
the Lorentz symmetry.

00:14:49.167 --> 00:14:50.750
In particular, that
breaks Lorentzian.

00:14:50.750 --> 00:14:55.080
So the nice thing about the
Neumann boundary condition

00:14:55.080 --> 00:14:58.160
we did before, in more
directions, so that

00:14:58.160 --> 00:15:00.520
respects Lorentz symmetry.

00:15:00.520 --> 00:15:03.660
And once we introduce some
directions to the Dirichlet

00:15:03.660 --> 00:15:05.520
boundary condition,
you necessarily

00:15:05.520 --> 00:15:12.080
break Lorentz symmetry, because
we select out some directions

00:15:12.080 --> 00:15:13.320
with some others.

00:15:13.320 --> 00:15:14.770
OK?

00:15:14.770 --> 00:15:17.620
And so you necessarily
break Lorentz symmetry.

00:15:17.620 --> 00:15:22.520
You also break translation
symmetry because of the-- you

00:15:22.520 --> 00:15:24.390
have to specify
some sub-manifold.

00:15:24.390 --> 00:15:28.500
You also break the
translation symmetry.

00:15:28.500 --> 00:15:32.420
So at first sight, this seems
to be a nonsensical thing to do.

00:15:32.420 --> 00:15:35.080
So that's why, for many
years, actually people did not

00:15:35.080 --> 00:15:42.170
look at this object,
even though for a person

00:15:42.170 --> 00:15:46.990
to work out string
theory on the first day,

00:15:46.990 --> 00:15:50.354
you should already realize those
are the boundary conditions.

00:15:50.354 --> 00:15:51.770
But for many years,
people did not

00:15:51.770 --> 00:15:54.582
pay attention to this kind
of boundary conditions.

00:15:54.582 --> 00:15:59.680
It turns out that
standard of conditions

00:15:59.680 --> 00:16:03.410
plays a key role
in string theory.

00:16:03.410 --> 00:16:09.640
And the key is to take a
slight different perspective

00:16:09.640 --> 00:16:11.650
at [INAUDIBLE] sub-manifold.

00:16:11.650 --> 00:16:13.910
OK?

00:16:13.910 --> 00:16:16.070
So now what you
should think about

00:16:16.070 --> 00:16:20.490
is-- and now what you think
about is the following.

00:16:23.170 --> 00:16:28.350
So you think about maybe
for the whole spacetime,

00:16:28.350 --> 00:16:32.200
the whole spacetime,
only closed string

00:16:32.200 --> 00:16:35.525
is the most natural object,
because it can move anywhere.

00:16:38.810 --> 00:16:42.930
But then there's
some special places

00:16:42.930 --> 00:16:47.860
in the spacetime,
some kind of defect.

00:16:47.860 --> 00:16:50.690
And at those defect,
the closed string

00:16:50.690 --> 00:16:53.490
can break to become open string.

00:16:53.490 --> 00:16:54.640
OK?

00:16:54.640 --> 00:16:56.840
Can become open string.

00:16:56.840 --> 00:16:59.017
And if you take
that perspective,

00:16:59.017 --> 00:17:00.850
then that gives special
meaning to such kind

00:17:00.850 --> 00:17:03.950
of special sub-manifold
which open string can end,

00:17:03.950 --> 00:17:07.000
then there's some
kind of object there.

00:17:07.000 --> 00:17:10.119
Because of the existence
of certain object there,

00:17:10.119 --> 00:17:15.450
then the open string
can end there.

00:17:15.450 --> 00:17:16.290
OK?

00:17:16.290 --> 00:17:16.834
Yes.

